  "signature": "ed25519:5cd41390053a60a1b284f362f97839d42d5d26be5dcb2a433d39d52d7c7e29857e8be3122b93f2159a07176515ff5ee2ed4f72db3ac5628aa08a6a7ae1510403",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-level2",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2, DePuy Synthes internal solver) operate under documented software quality management systems. FDA code under 21 CFR Part 11 controls; Ansys holds ISO 9001 certification with V&V documentation; DePuy Synthes solver validated per IEC 62304 Class B. Version control, change management, and regression test suites demonstrated for each. Gradation 2 achieved: documented SQA plans with formal testing records available."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/ncv-level2",
      "rationale": "Patch test, single-element tests, and benchmark comparisons against NAFEMS standard problems (LE1, LE10) conducted for all three solvers. Ansys Mechanical verified against analytic Euler-Bernoulli beam solutions for the titanium rod geometry; maximum error 0.3%. FDA solver verified against closed-form contact mechanics solutions. Gradation 3 achieved: independent code-to-code comparison across all three FEA implementations shows < 2% deviation on all QoIs, providing cross-verification evidence beyond Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/disc-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study performed on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry using three systematically refined meshes (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements). Richardson extrapolation applied; Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for stiffness QoI = 0.8%, for yield force QoI = 1.1%. Production mesh (medium refinement) selected with demonstrated convergence. Gradation 3 achieved: formal GCI analysis with documented convergence ratios and extrapolated reference solutions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver (Newton-Raphson with arc-length control for post-yield regime) convergence verified via force and displacement residual norms < 1e-6 at each load increment. Contact algorithm (augmented Lagrangian) convergence confirmed with penetration tolerance < 0.001 mm. Time integration not applicable (quasi-static analysis). Gradation 2 achieved: solver convergence metrics documented and within prescribed tolerances for all 11 construct configurations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow executed by two independent analysts using documented simulation protocols. Boundary condition application, material property assignment, and contact definition reviewed by a third analyst. Model setup checklist completed and archived for each of the 11 construct configurations. Peer review of input decks conducted prior to production runs. Gradation 2 achieved: independent analyst review with documented checklist verification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-level3",
      "rationale": "Continuum FEA with elastic-perfectly-plastic titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) material model and bilinear isotropic hardening for UHMWPE vertebral body surrogates. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at all screw-rod and screw-vertebral body interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity (large deformation) enabled for post-yield regime. Model form justified by comparison to published literature on pedicle screw FEA and by the fact that dominant failure mode (rod bending/yielding) is well captured by the chosen constitutive model. Gradation 3 achieved: model form uncertainty assessed via sensitivity analysis showing < 5% QoI sensitivity to constitutive model parameter variations within physically plausible bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-level3",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, ultimate strength) sourced from lot-specific coupon testing of the same titanium alloy rod stock used in bench specimens. UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate properties from manufacturer data sheet with independent verification testing (n=5 coupons). Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of actual test specimens (n=5 representative constructs). Uncertainty distributions assigned to all primary inputs; Latin hypercube sampling (n=200) used for input uncertainty propagation. Gradation 3 achieved: input uncertainty fully characterized with traceable measurement data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-level3",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production-representative components (same design, same manufacturing lot as clinical device). Constructs assembled by two independent technicians following ASTM F1717 assembly protocol. Sample-to-sample geometric variability characterized by CMM measurement of all 11 constructs. Statistical summary of key geometric parameters (rod diameter, screw thread geometry, construct height) provided. Gradation 3 achieved: sample characterization sufficient to populate model input distributions and assess sample representativeness."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-level2",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single test condition per ASTM F1717 (quasi-static compression-bending, 5 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature 23±2°C). While the standard prescribes this single condition, the COU is limited to this specific loading scenario and no other conditions are claimed. Load cell calibration traceable to NIST; displacement measurement via crosshead encoder with independent extensometer verification on 3 of 11 constructs. Gradation 2 achieved (below required Gradation 3): only one test condition evaluated; multi-rate or multi-temperature testing not performed. This acknowledged shortfall is accepted given that the COU is explicitly scoped to the ASTM F1717 standard condition and the model influence is Medium."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/equiv-inputs-level3",
      "rationale": "Direct correspondence established between all model input parameters and experimental measurements. Material properties in FEA assigned from lot-specific test data; geometric parameters in FEA assigned from CMM measurements of the same physical constructs used in bench testing. Boundary conditions (fixed inferior vertebral body, axial compressive load applied at superior body centroid at 5-degree caudal angulation) replicate ASTM F1717 fixture constraints as verified by fixture CAD drawings. Torque applied to set screws in FEA (4 Nm) matches bench assembly records. Gradation 3 achieved: one-to-one traceability between all simulation inputs and experimental measurements documented in the simulation record."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-level3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed for all three primary QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval. Experimental uncertainty uexp estimated from inter-specimen variability (coefficient of variation 4–8% across QoIs); simulation uncertainty usim estimated from input uncertainty propagation (LHS n=200). Combined validation uncertainty uval = sqrt(uexp^2 + usim^2). All three E/uval values < 1.96 (stiffness: 0.81, yield force: 1.34, force at 40 mm: 1.12). Load-displacement curves compared graphically across all 11 constructs. Gradation 3 achieved: full uncertainty-normalized comparison with documented acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-level3",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary performance endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the clinical decision context (structural adequacy of the pedicle screw construct under physiological compression-bending loads). Stiffness characterizes immediate post-implantation load sharing; yield force defines the onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm is the standard failure metric. All three QoIs are directly observable in both simulation and experiment with no intermediate inference steps. Gradation 3 achieved: QoIs are the same quantities used in the regulatory submission and are directly clinically interpretable."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/val-relevance-level3",
      "rationale": "Validation activity directly replicates the COU: same device design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw), same loading modality (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), same material system, same assembly protocol. The FEA model validated here is the same model (same code, same material models, same meshing strategy) used for the COU prediction — no extrapolation of validation evidence required. Two independent laboratories provide geographic and equipment diversity. Gradation 3 achieved: validation activities are directly applicable to the COU without requiring similarity arguments or extrapolation."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, ASTM F1717 compression-bending) is accepted at the Medium assurance level commensurate with a Model Risk Level 3 device (Class II, Medium model influence, Medium decision consequence). Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. The single factor below required level (Test conditions, achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) is explicitly acknowledged and accepted on the basis that: (1) the COU is scoped exclusively to the ASTM F1717 standard test condition, making multi-condition testing unnecessary for the stated claim; (2) the model influence is Medium, not High; and (3) all three validation metrics (E/uval for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement) are well within the 1.96 acceptance threshold, providing high confidence in model predictive accuracy under the claimed condition. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through uncertainty quantification to validation metric computation is complete and traceable. The FEA ensemble (three independent codes) provides additional confidence through cross-verification. The assessment team concludes that the simulation evidence is sufficient to support the intended regulatory use.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
